* Adding a new API in MXNet backend - `data_names, data_shapes = get_mxnet_model_info(model)` for users to be able to query MXNet backend to see what is underlying MXNet model metadata. 
* This API is typically useful for users using MXNetModelCheckpoint to save best model as native MXNet model but, through checkpoint they can't get the MXNet model details. So they will use this API for fetching those details to bind to MXNet module.

@kalyc @roywei

**Fix - #1571 If service in VIP mode, Network Aliases needs to be populated with hostname.**

When using the standard docker CLI utility to deploy a docker stack `(docker stack deploy)` a JSON is always generated with an Aliases argument in the ["TaskTemplate"]["Networks"] dictionary when deployed in VIP mode.

Example shown here of JSON output from `docker stack deploy` CLI deployment.
```
"TaskTemplate" : {
    "Networks": [
      {
        "Target": "wlydwxqc5hwprwpktofo8le68",
        "Aliases": [
          "manager"]
      }],
}
```

Example shown here using high-level docker-py service creation `(client.service.create)`

```
"TaskTemplate" : {
    "Networks": [
      {
        "Target": "wlydwxqc5hwprwpktofo8le68"
      }]
}
```

Without Aliases in VIP mode, `dockerd` internal DNS resolver will be unable to resolve adjacent services on adjacent nodes in the swarm configuration. This has been verified with packet capture.

If you would like to reproduce this for yourselves, deploy a two service stack using the command line on a overlay network driver, view the service attrs and check the Networks within TaskTemplate. Now deploy this same stack using docker-py in VIP mode on a overlay network, Aliases will not appear in `service.attrs` and internal DNS resolution will fail.

This hack is pretty ugly, fixup as you wish, but please fix.

As discussed in #774, this PR changes the module initialization macro from:

```c++
PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    pybind11::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");
    m.def("add", [](int a, int b) { return a + b; });
    return m.ptr();
}
```
to:
```c++
PYBIND11_MODULE(example, m) {
    m.doc() = "pybind11 example plugin";
    m.def("add", [](int a, int b) { return a + b; });
}
```

Notes:

* Using the old macro results in a deprecation warning. The warning actually points to the `pybind11_init` function (since attributes don't bind to macros), but the message should be quite clear: "PYBIND11_PLUGIN is deprecated, use PYBIND11_MODULE".
* The docs have been updated to reflect the change. This makes one less entry in the FAQ.
* `doc()` is implemented as a simple shortcut for the `attr("__doc__")` accessor.

